\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since addition of vectors is commutative, it does not matter which vector
 is plotted first.
 After the pair of displacements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
5\\
0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, Victor's total displacement is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
5+\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 In the diagram, the gray vectors represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
5\\
0
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and the blue vectors represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
5\\
0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The five vectors together illustrate the parallelogram rule for vector
 addition.
 The sum of two vectors is a diagonal of the parallelogram determined by
 the two vectors.
\end_layout

